There’s a strong cognitive-science version of what you’re describing.

Attention acts like a filter and weighting system:

* it selects what becomes salient,
* suppresses other signals,
* and influences how ambiguous information gets interpreted.

Two people can look at the same scene and perceive very different things because their:

* expectations,
* emotional state,
* memories,
* goals,
* training,
* and attentional habits
    shape interpretation.

Humans are also pattern-completion machines. We often understand the external world partly by projecting internal models onto it. That’s not necessarily delusion — it’s how perception works. The brain continuously compares:

* incoming sensory data
    against
* internal predictions and learned structures.

So yes, people often “recognize themselves” in the world:

* artists in landscapes,
* scientists in equations,
* mystics in symbols,
* engineers in systems,
* storytellers in history.

The Möbius-strip idea fits metaphorically because the boundary between:

* internal model
    and
* external interpretation
    isn’t perfectly clean. Perception is a loop:
    world influences mind,
    mind shapes interpretation of world,
    interpretation changes action,
    action changes future world exposure.

But it’s still important to maintain friction with reality. Internal patterns can illuminate the world, but they can also overfit it. The healthiest perception systems stay open to correction instead of assuming every observed pattern is a reflection of the self.